{
  "What is the SI unit of magnetic field strength?": "",
  "Tesla": "",
  "Newton": "",
  "Ampere": "",
  "Coulomb": "",
  "The SI unit of magnetic field strength (magnetic flux density) is the Tesla (T), where 1 T = 1 kg/(A*s^2).": "",
  "A current-carrying wire placed in a magnetic field experiences a force. This force is maximum when the angle between the current and field is:": "",
  "45 degrees": "",
  "90 degrees": "",
  "0 degrees": "",
  "180 degrees": "",
  "The magnetic force on a current-carrying wire is F = BIL*sin(theta). The force is maximum when theta = 90 degrees (sin 90 = 1), i.e., when the current is perpendicular to the field.": "",
  "Magnetic field lines around a bar magnet go from:": "",
  "They form straight lines from one pole": "",
  "North pole to south pole outside the magnet": "",
  "They only exist inside the magnet": "",
  "South pole to north pole outside the magnet": "",
  "By convention, magnetic field lines emerge from the north pole and enter the south pole outside the magnet. Inside the magnet, they go from south to north, forming closed loops.": "",
  "The magnetic force on a stationary electric charge in a magnetic field is:": "",
  "Zero": "",
  "Equal to qB": "",
  "Maximum": "",
  "Dependent on the charge magnitude": "",
  "The magnetic force on a charge is F = qvB*sin(theta). If the charge is stationary (v = 0), the force is zero. Magnetic fields only exert forces on moving charges.": "",
  "The right-hand rule for a current-carrying wire in a magnetic field gives the direction of:": "",
  "The electric field": "",
  "The magnetic force on the wire": "",
  "The current": "",
  "The magnetic field": "",
  "The right-hand rule: point fingers in the direction of current (or velocity for a positive charge), curl them toward B, and the thumb points in the direction of the force (F = IL x B).": "",
  "A long straight wire carrying current creates a magnetic field whose strength:": "",
  "Decreases with the square of distance": "",
  "Is constant at all distances": "",
  "Increases with distance from the wire": "",
  "Decreases inversely with distance from the wire": "",
  "The magnetic field around a long straight wire is B = mu_0*I/(2*pi*r), which decreases inversely with distance r from the wire.": "",
  "Two parallel wires carrying currents in the same direction will:": "",
  "Repel each other": "",
  "Have no interaction": "",
  "Rotate around each other": "",
  "Attract each other": "",
  "Two parallel wires carrying currents in the same direction attract each other. Each wire's magnetic field exerts a force on the other wire directed toward it.": "",
  "The magnetic field inside a solenoid is:": "",
  "Circular around the axis": "",
  "Non-uniform and varies with position": "",
  "Approximately uniform and parallel to the axis": "",
  "Inside an ideal solenoid, the magnetic field is approximately uniform and directed along the axis of the solenoid. B = mu_0 * n * I, where n is the number of turns per unit length.": "",
  "Which of the following is NOT a source of magnetic fields?": "",
  "A moving electric charge": "",
  "A current-carrying wire": "",
  "A permanent magnet": "",
  "A stationary electric charge": "",
  "A stationary electric charge creates an electric field but not a magnetic field. Magnetic fields are produced by moving charges, currents, and permanent magnets.": "",
  "The force on a current-carrying wire of length L in a uniform magnetic field B is given by:": "",
  "F = BIL sin(theta)": "",
  "F = BIL cos(theta)": "",
  "F = B^2IL": "",
  "F = qvB": "",
  "The force on a current-carrying wire in a magnetic field is F = BIL*sin(theta), where theta is the angle between the current direction and the magnetic field.": "",
  "What is a magnetic field?": "",
  "The same as an electric field": "",
  "A field that only exists inside magnets": "",
  "A region where electric charges are stationary": "",
  "A region of space where a moving charge or current-carrying conductor experiences a force": "",
  "A magnetic field is a vector field that describes the magnetic influence on moving electric charges, electric currents, and magnetic materials in the surrounding space.": "",
  "What is magnetic flux?": "",
  "The total magnetic field strength at a point": "",
  "The product of magnetic field strength and the area through which it passes, accounting for the angle: Phi = BA*cos(theta)": "",
  "The current produced by a magnetic field": "",
  "The force on a wire in a magnetic field": "",
  "Magnetic flux (Phi) measures the total magnetic field passing through a surface area. It is calculated as Phi = BA*cos(theta), where theta is the angle between B and the area normal. Its SI unit is the Weber (Wb).": "",
  "What is a solenoid?": "",
  "A permanent magnet shaped like a cylinder regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "A device that measures magnetic field strength, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "A single loop of wire carrying current, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "A coil of wire with many turns wound in a helix, creating a nearly uniform magnetic field inside when current flows through it": "",
  "A solenoid is a long coil of wire wound in a helix. When current flows through it, it produces a nearly uniform magnetic field inside (B = mu_0*n*I) similar to a bar magnet.": "",
  "What is the permeability of free space (mu_0)?": "",
  "The speed of light in a vacuum because conventional analysis of free suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "The resistance of a vacuum to electric current, particularly in the context of free": "",
  "The electric constant of free space, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "A fundamental constant that relates magnetic field strength to the current and geometry that produce it, equal to 4*pi*10^-7 T*m/A": "",
  "The permeability of free space (mu_0 = 4*pi*10^-7 T*m/A) is a fundamental constant that appears in equations relating magnetic fields to the currents that produce them.": "",
  "What is the right-hand rule for a straight current-carrying wire?": "",
  "Point all fingers in the direction of current to find the force direction": "",
  "The right-hand rule only applies to solenoids, not straight wires": "",
  "Point the thumb in the direction of the magnetic field; the fingers curl in the direction of current": "",
  "Point the thumb in the direction of conventional current; the curled fingers indicate the direction of the circular magnetic field around the wire": "",
  "For a straight current-carrying wire, point your right thumb in the direction of conventional current. Your curled fingers then indicate the direction of the circular magnetic field lines around the wire.": "",
  "What is magnetic domain theory?": "",
  "A theory about how magnetic fields propagate through space, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "The explanation that ferromagnetic materials contain small regions (domains) of aligned atomic magnetic moments, and magnetization occurs when these domains align": "",
  "A mathematical model for calculating magnetic field lines, based on conventional assumptions about magnetic": "",
  "The theory that magnetic monopoles exist, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing magnetic dynamics": "",
  "Magnetic domain theory explains that ferromagnetic materials consist of many small regions (domains) where atomic magnetic moments are aligned. An external field can cause domains to grow or rotate, magnetizing the material.": "",
  "What is the Biot-Savart law?": "",
  "A law about electromagnetic induction": "",
  "A law relating electric field to charge distribution": "",
  "A law governing magnetic monopoles": "",
  "A law that gives the magnetic field produced by a small segment of current-carrying wire at a point in space": "",
  "The Biot-Savart law calculates the magnetic field dB produced by an infinitesimal current element: dB = (mu_0/4pi) * I*dL x r_hat / r^2. It is the magnetic analog of Coulomb's law.": "",
  "What is Ampere's law?": "",
  "The force between two charges is proportional to their product": "",
  "The line integral of the magnetic field around a closed loop equals mu_0 times the enclosed current": "",
  "A changing magnetic field produces an electric field": "",
  "The total magnetic flux through a closed surface is zero": "",
  "Ampere's law states that the line integral of B around any closed path (Amperian loop) equals mu_0 times the total current enclosed: integral B*dL = mu_0*I_enclosed.": "",
  "What is a magnetic dipole?": "",
  "A wire carrying alternating current according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "An object with two magnetic poles (north and south) that creates a magnetic field, such as a bar magnet or current loop": "",
  "Two electric charges separated by a distance, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "A single isolated magnetic pole, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "A magnetic dipole is an entity with a north and south pole that generates a dipole magnetic field. Examples include bar magnets, current loops, and electrons (due to spin). Isolated magnetic monopoles have never been observed.": "",
  "What is ferromagnetism?": "",
  "A property of all metals in magnetic fields": "",
  "The property of materials that are weakly repelled by magnetic fields": "",
  "The property of certain materials (like iron, nickel, cobalt) that can be strongly magnetized and retain magnetization due to aligned magnetic domains": "",
  "The generation of magnetic fields by electric currents only": "",
  "Ferromagnetism is the property of materials like iron, nickel, and cobalt that can be strongly magnetized. Their atomic magnetic moments align within domains, and these domains can be aligned by an external field, creating strong permanent magnets.": "",
  "A 0.5-m wire carrying 3 A of current is placed perpendicular to a uniform 0.2 T magnetic field. What is the magnitude of the force on the wire?": "",
  "0.60 N": "",
  "0.30 N": "",
  "0.15 N": "",
  "3.0 N": "",
  "F = BIL*sin(theta) = 0.2 * 3 * 0.5 * sin(90) = 0.30 N.": "",
  "A solenoid has 500 turns over a length of 0.25 m and carries a current of 2 A. What is the magnetic field inside the solenoid?": "",
  "2.51 * 10^-3 T": "",
  "1.0 * 10^-2 T": "",
  "1.26 * 10^-3 T": "",
  "5.03 * 10^-3 T": "",
  "B = mu_0 * n * I = (4*pi*10^-7)(500/0.25)(2) = (4*pi*10^-7)(2000)(2) = 5.03 * 10^-3 T.": "",
  "Two parallel wires are 0.1 m apart. Wire 1 carries 5 A and Wire 2 carries 10 A in the same direction. What is the force per unit length between them?": "",
  "2.0 * 10^-4 N/m, attractive": "",
  "1.0 * 10^-4 N/m, attractive": "",
  "1.0 * 10^-4 N/m, repulsive": "",
  "5.0 * 10^-5 N/m, repulsive": "",
  "F/L = mu_0*I1*I2/(2*pi*d) = (4*pi*10^-7)(5)(10)/(2*pi*0.1) = 1.0 * 10^-4 N/m. Same-direction currents attract.": "",
  "A wire carrying 4 A is oriented at 30 degrees to a 0.5 T magnetic field. If the wire is 0.3 m long, what force does it experience?": "",
  "0.52 N": "",
  "F = BIL*sin(theta) = 0.5 * 4 * 0.3 * sin(30) = 0.5 * 4 * 0.3 * 0.5 = 0.30 N.": "",
  "An MRI machine requires a uniform magnetic field of 1.5 T inside a solenoid of length 2 m. If the solenoid carries 100 A, how many turns of wire are needed?": "",
  "About 47,800 turns": "",
  "About 6,000 turns": "",
  "About 12,000 turns": "",
  "About 23,900 turns": "",
  "B = mu_0*n*I, so n = B/(mu_0*I) = 1.5/(4*pi*10^-7 * 100) = 11,937 turns/m. Total turns = n*L = 11,937 * 2 = 23,873 turns, approximately 23,900.": "",
  "A scientist measures the magnetic field 5 cm from a long straight wire carrying 15 A. What is the field strength?": "",
  "1.2 * 10^-4 T": "",
  "6.0 * 10^-5 T": "",
  "3.0 * 10^-5 T": "",
  "9.4 * 10^-5 T": "",
  "B = mu_0*I/(2*pi*r) = (4*pi*10^-7)(15)/(2*pi*0.05) = (2*10^-7)(15)/0.05 = 6.0 * 10^-5 T.": "",
  "A rectangular loop (0.2 m by 0.1 m) carrying 5 A is placed in a uniform 0.4 T field with the plane of the loop perpendicular to the field. What is the net force on the loop?": "",
  "0 N": "",
  "0.2 N": "",
  "0.04 N": "",
  "0.4 N": "",
  "In a uniform magnetic field, the net force on a complete current loop is zero because the forces on opposite sides cancel. However, there may be a net torque on the loop.": "",
  "An engineer designs an electromagnet by wrapping 200 turns of wire around a 0.1-m iron core. The current is 3 A. If the relative permeability of iron is 5000, what is the magnetic field inside the core?": "",
  "7.54 T": "",
  "3.77 T": "",
  "0.377 T": "",
  "37.7 T": "",
  "B = mu_r * mu_0 * n * I = 5000 * (4*pi*10^-7) * (200/0.1) * 3 = 5000 * (4*pi*10^-7) * 2000 * 3 = 5000 * 7.54*10^-3 = 37.7 T.": "",
  "A current balance experiment uses a 0.15-m wire segment carrying 8 A in a 0.25 T field (perpendicular). The wire is on a balance. What mass would produce an equivalent gravitational force?": "",
  "0.30 kg": "",
  "0.031 kg": "",
  "0.015 kg": "",
  "0.061 kg": "",
  "F = BIL = 0.25 * 8 * 0.15 = 0.30 N. Setting mg = F: m = F/g = 0.30/9.8 = 0.0306 kg ≈ 0.031 kg.": "",
  "A lab technician creates a Helmholtz coil pair (two identical coils separated by their radius R = 0.2 m). Each coil has 50 turns and carries 2 A. The field at the midpoint between Helmholtz coils is approximately B = 0.9 * mu_0 * N * I / R. What is the field at the center?": "",
  "1.41 * 10^-4 T": "",
  "1.13 * 10^-3 T": "",
  "2.83 * 10^-4 T": "",
  "5.65 * 10^-4 T": "",
  "B = 0.9 * mu_0 * N * I / R = 0.9 * (4*pi*10^-7) * 50 * 2 / 0.2 = 0.9 * 6.28*10^-4 = 5.65 * 10^-4 T.": ""
